See, I think this experiment works, especially nowadays, because people forget to get to know each other when they're in the dating process. The emphasis on technology and seeming disregard for actual conversation and human interaction kind of kills what used to be the best way to date - which is simply getting to know one another. I don't really believe that it's this specific combination of questions that makes people fall in love, I think it's the idea behind conversation and eye contact without constant attention given to devices that plays a key role.

I also agree with other people who have said that the two people should not know about the experiment beforehand. That really does mess with the results and the expectations of the test subjects. Who's to say that the people who created this video didn't specifically choose people who had a ton in common so that they would really like each other? Who knows.

I still really liked this video. I think it would be really interesting to see an actually, full-blown example of this experiment with all 36 questions and with neither test subject knowing what they were going to do.

This actually works, I'm not going to lie. One night after a particularly bad day I ran into this guy I went on two atrocious dates with  a few years ago and deciding it might end up being a good distraction I agreed to grab a coffee with him. When the conversation hit a lull he pulled out his phone and looked up what he said was a list of random questions to play 20 questions with - all of which in hindsight are in this experiment. Now I'd like to stress just how awful my previous experiences with this guy were, we have absolutely nothing in common and I later found out an almost uncomfortable age difference. At the end of these questions my opinion of him - briefly - changed. Took a complete 180. We spent the next week almost inseparable, talking on the phone until 4 am if I wasn't already over at his place. My friends had no clue what had gotten into me, my dates with the guy were so bad they were legendary in my circle of friends and suddenly I went from thinking he was crazy to being crazy about him. Thankfully, he was in the process of relocating for work around the same time my friends came home for Christmas break and what I can only describe as temporary insanity came to an end. Imagine my surprise when I found about this experiment, it's absolutely insane.

For instance, not many people have developed personalities and some of the questions here would be hard to answer without personality. Also, a couple of questions(the mom one and a few others) are a bit too personal for strangers. What I want to say is that in order to use this casualy, without telling the other person "can you partake in this experiment?", the questions need to be reformulated and simplified just a little bit, and the "we are..." is just stupid and requires far too much brainpower, which will slow the "game" down and the potential partner will lose interest. If you want to score quickly and are unusure if you want a further relationship then you're gonna have to formulate these questions in a manner that hides a great deal of your identity and history. Not a scientist here's my "opinion."
You can love anyone. Love is simply compassion for another and the willingness to make at least some sacrifice for them. You can love your wife to the point that you'd die for them, your girlfriend enough that you'd sacrifice a night out with your friends to stay comfort them through a tough time, or a girl you just met enough to shield them under your umbrella when its raining. The more we get to know someone, the more we are able to love them, as they change our lives and we really see the goodness in their character. So, of course a series of deep questions that's designed to explore a person's deepest thoughts or most secret memories will allow you to love a person much easier. It's basically months or years of friendship summed up into a 36 questions.

Love should be the basis of any relationship whether between a couple or friends. Not to mention that most people don't want to leave another person after talking with them for an hour, let alone learning so much about them. So of course they would set up dates, because who wouldn't want to meet up with a person again after doing this entire survey? Especially if they're not only attractive, but their both viewing this as a romantic experience, instead of just one that does not need to be romantic if not suggested to be such (and they're both single looking to be in a relationship). And personally, I would never kiss a girl after we just met an hour or so ago. I think they probably don't see kissing as that special of an act (or at least as special as it can be made to be), and therefore would probably kiss if they had been asked any other questions to simply break the ice and develop some sort of relationship.

I have an objection for the set up of the study, from what I got from the video. I think the subject's responses would have been much more genuine if they were not briefed beforehand. I can understand why this may be a weird study to sign into blind ('hey ask this random guy some random questions'), but the subjects know the study was about falling in love, indicated by the woman saying "I really want to see if the study works." This tells us that they were already thinking about falling in love because of the questions specifically, and so the focus on the questions was much more intense. This would probably be different from a regular first date, since the expectations wouldn't be so specifically based around the questions themselves, but more generally based around all the normal factors of a first date.
Essentially, this study started out with giving the subjects a hint of extra bias towards the questions in order to (I would assume) isolate the 'questions' and perhaps physical attractiveness variables from all the others one may encounter or be subjected to on a normal date. Of course, in a real date, special attention is (probably) payed to the way the other person answers questions, but it is very unlikely that a random first-date-couple would ask a set of questions to each other with the claim in their mind that that specific set of questions could "make strangers fall in love."

Really, the questions are knowing someone from the inside and not cuz of the way they look which either makes you like them or not based on the answers you'd get. So, it's a win win situation. Either you connect deeper with that individual or go your separate ways which helps to figure out way sooner if they are right for you or not. It's common sense to ask questions you'd normally wouldn't and to see who likes you for it. Makes a longer, lasting love relationship.

Well this makes sense. At least for me. I personally think most girls are at least somewhat attractive and the deciding factor is how much time I spend with them and as a consequence how well i get to know them. If I can have a long conversation about myself, each other or some weirdly deep topic then it's a win. Then I just need some hints that she feels the same way and I'll be ready to confess.

In this experiment they are both at least willing to participate so they are not completely randomly selected, therefore they likely have more stuff in common than a completely random couple. They talk about themselves so they get to know each other and they talk about their opinions about the other person. Since they willingly accepted to participate there is not much reason to lie or keep up an image.

The two biggest challenges with love are getting to know somebody enough to actually fall in love and after that to maintain the relationship. That last part is what makes someone "the right one". Though the first problem was eliminated by this experiment the second one is not and it's almost impossible to test that in a controlled environment suitable for scientific research. That is why love still has that magical feel to it even though science has ruined most of it with hormones, pheromones and psychology.

my scientific explanation to these question's effectiveness:
- they are pretty personal, if slipped into a regular conversation, they could work pretty well
- despite being personal, they have 2 distinct characteristics:
a) both the person asking and person answering can answer the question, which helps share information between the two sides
b) the questions are super simple, and thus the person answering them will see them as that, not realizing that they're practically sharing personal information or sometimes even small secrets.
- following "b)", the person sharing the personal information will subconciously develop trust towards the person asking them the questions as they answer more and more of those. trust eventually leads to the person being perfectly comfortable with the other, which increases the likelihood of them falling in love and/or completely skipping the rest of the "personality test" they're doing on the stranger, and start looking directly into the person's appearance more thoroughly.
- contrary to popular belief, you do not really get your impression off of someone's looks/attractiveness, you do that only if you pass them by really fast or they have something distinct about them (like crazy looking hair, or maybe a deformity somewhere, or the level of their tidiness/hygiene) otherwise, in a stranger-to-stranger conversation, personality plays the dominant role for the impression, once you get that impression (which is significantly sped up by the questions giving trust more easily), you start noticing the attractive things about the person (remember, a good personality impression will drive the person to focus on your physical "perfections" and more than likely ignore the imperfections, thus, they fall in love)

The reason that this works is that all the questions are geared to put many of the persons inner feelings out there for the other to know and sympathize with.
This methodology completely shatters the typical social contract people have with each other in everyday life. It's also happening in a strange place under strange circumstances, something each person can relate to and gets them in the same frame of mind.
Also since they are in this particular situation there is an inherent trust involved with what everyone is saying. This will make each participant more receptive to what the other is saying and start forming a lasting bond.

Essentially all the normal social and mental roadblocks are torn down and allow each person to interact extremely candidly with the other.

Telling them ahead of time what the whole thing is about doesn't hurt the chances either. Confirmation bias anyone?

If this wasn't staged it might as well had been because they were handpicked for maximum compatibility. they're both good looking young people, same race, and same kind of calm, grounded, no quirks average personality. It's not a case of miraculous questions at work. These are the questions that come up naturally throughout various dates. All you did was handpick two seemingly similar people, probably both looking for someone to date, and forced them to know eachother. The fact that they're both good looking really just facilitates the whole thing, including the kiss at the end. Besides, the whole thing was rigged the moment they knew the point of the experience was to see if they fall in love with each other. they were conditioned to interpret the experience as courtship, and since there are these "sciencey" magic questions involved, the placebo effect is very likely to happen. Seriously, you just facilitated the interaction between two people who'd proably date eachother anyway in a normal setting, if given the chance.
